land":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cherleton, Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","near Wellington, Shropshire, England":"Wellington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cherleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Charlton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Charlton","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): habitational name from North Charlton or Charlton near Bellingham (both Northumberland) or from any of the many other places so named (there are over ninety examples in England), from Old English <i>Ceorlatūn</i> ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) of the peasants’. Old English <i>ceorl</i> denoted originally a free peasant of the lowest rank, later (but probably already before the Norman conquest) a tenant in pure villeinage, a serf or bondsman.","Irish: altered form of   Carlin  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":5,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":36,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Cherleton was born in 1254, in Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Cherleton, was 20 and his mother, Anne de Holland, was 30. He married Elinor Holland in 1274, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1300, in Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1254–1300":"1254–1300","1254–1328":"1254–1328","1268–1353":"1268–1353","1269–1344":"1269–1344","1278–1322":"1278–1322","1278–1360":"1278–1360","1234–1263":"1234–1263","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1263":"1263","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1268":"1268","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","1234":"1234","1322":"1322","1344":"1344","1254":"1254","1353":"1353","1328":"1328","Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Cherleton, Wrockwardine, Shropshire, England":"Wrockwardine, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","near Wellington, Shropshire, England":"Wellington, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1254–1300":"1254–1300","1254–1328":"1254–1328","1268–1353":"1268–1353","1269–1344":"1269–1344","1278–1322":"1278–1322","1278–1360":"1278–1360","1234–1263":"1234–1263","1224–Female":"1224–Kuollut","1263":"1263","1